docs.abstract: At a fund-raiser in the Hamptons, President Trump said that he had expected Jerome H. Powell to adhere to an easy-money monetary policy, by keeping interest rates low, when he nominated him.
docs.snippet: At a fund-raiser in the Hamptons, President Trump said that he had expected Jerome H. Powell to adhere to an easy-money monetary policy, by keeping interest rates low, when he nominated him.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump complained to wealthy donors at a fund-raiser in the Hamptons last week that the man he chose as chairman of the Federal Reserve, Jerome H. Powell, has disappointed him by raising interest rates, according to people who attended the event.

headline.main: Trump Complains About Fed Chairman’s Raising of Interest Rates
headline.print_headline: Trump Complains to Donors That His Federal Reserve Chairman Is Raising Interest Rates

byline.original: By Jim Tankersley and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: Regulators charged a second former worker, accusing him of buying stock options before the breach of 140 million consumers’ data became public.
docs.snippet: Regulators charged a second former worker, accusing him of buying stock options before the breach of 140 million consumers’ data became public.
docs.lead_paragraph: Regulators charged a second former Equifax employee with insider trading, accusing him on Thursday of placing a financial bet that the stock would decline after learning about the company’s huge data breach but before it was publicly disclosed.

headline.main: Another Equifax Employee Faces Charge of Insider Trading After Big Breach
headline.print_headline: Equifax Worker Charged With Insider Stock Trade

docs.abstract: The investing giant accelerated a price war by introducing two index mutual funds with no fees. If the move works, Fidelity can sell other products and services to those it attracts.
docs.snippet: The investing giant accelerated a price war by introducing two index mutual funds with no fees. If the move works, Fidelity can sell other products and services to those it attracts.
docs.lead_paragraph: Investing just became even cheaper — free, actually.

headline.main: Fidelity Tries Luring Investors With 2 No-Fee Funds. So What’s the Catch?
headline.print_headline: Fidelity Offers 2 No-Fee Funds As ‘Bait,’ Accelerating Price War

docs.abstract: Top executives have long been enlisted, to very good effect, to star in commercials for their companies. But it can be a fraught strategy, as the troubles at Papa John’s have shown.
docs.snippet: Top executives have long been enlisted, to very good effect, to star in commercials for their companies. But it can be a fraught strategy, as the troubles at Papa John’s have shown.
docs.lead_paragraph: Commercials for Dollar Shave Club, the subscription toiletries company, are known for two things. There’s that zany, slightly frat-boy sense of humor — the latest ad features a few dozen people shaving, tweezing, clipping, trimming, waxing, bathing, powdering, spritzing, gelling, styling and moisturizing to the song “I’ve Gotta Be Me” as crooned by Steve Lawrence.

headline.main: Warts and All? That’s the Risk When a Founder Is the Face of a Company
headline.print_headline: When the Founder Is the Face of the Company

docs.abstract: European officials are eager to paint Greece as a comeback story. But troubles in nearby Italy show that the euro’s issues have not been laid to rest.
docs.snippet: European officials are eager to paint Greece as a comeback story. But troubles in nearby Italy show that the euro’s issues have not been laid to rest.
docs.lead_paragraph: As Greece prepares to emerge from one of the region’s most wrenching economic periods, its creditors are drawing up plans to ensure it is never a problem for the rest of Europe again.

headline.main: As Greece Ends a Decade of Bailouts, Problems Linger for Europe
headline.print_headline: Greek Bailouts End, but the Eurozone’s Problems Linger

docs.abstract: Even though American and European executives are staying away, companies are unlikely to sever ties or avert future deals after the killing of Jamal Khashoggi.
docs.snippet: Even though American and European executives are staying away, companies are unlikely to sever ties or avert future deals after the killing of Jamal Khashoggi.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — Saudi Arabia is pouring $20 billion into a new investment fund run by Wall Street’s Blackstone Group. The French oil giant Total just inked a nine-billion-euro petrochemical deal with the kingdom. The British defense company BAE Systems is selling 48 Typhoon combat jets to Riyadh for an estimated five billion British pounds.

headline.main: C.E.O.s May Avoid Riyadh Conference but Not Saudi Money
headline.print_headline: Saudi Money Tightly Binds Some Giants Of Business

byline.original: By Liz Alderman and Michael J. de la Merced

docs.abstract: As Greece prepares to exit nearly a decade worth of bailouts, the International Monetary Fund is warning the country faces an uphill battle to recovery.
docs.snippet: As Greece prepares to exit nearly a decade worth of bailouts, the International Monetary Fund is warning the country faces an uphill battle to recovery.
docs.lead_paragraph: As Greece prepares to end nearly a decade’s worth of international financial bailouts next month, European policymakers have been eager to promote the country’s economic comeback story and the symbolic end of the region’s punishing debt crisis.

headline.main: Europe Says Greece Is a Comeback Story. The I.M.F. Isn’t Convinced.
headline.print_headline: Europe Says Greece Is a Comeback Story. The I.M.F. Isn’t Convinced.

docs.abstract: As polls numbers drop, President Emmanuel Macron promises benefits for middle- and low-income earners and tells investors he won’t halt economic reforms.
docs.snippet: As polls numbers drop, President Emmanuel Macron promises benefits for middle- and low-income earners and tells investors he won’t halt economic reforms.
docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — As President Emmanuel Macron presses ahead with the most business-friendly overhaul of the French labor market in decades, his popularity with many of his countrymen has gone into a tailspin. Consumer confidence is falling. A nascent recovery is cooling off. Unemployment has been stuck above 9 percent for months.

headline.main: Macron, With Popularity Slumping, Tries Tax Cuts for France’s Working Class
headline.print_headline: Macron, With Popularity Slumping, Tries Tax Cuts for French Workers

docs.abstract: As a new era of financial independence beckons, more than a third of the population is in poverty, unemployment remains high and wages have tumbled.
docs.snippet: As a new era of financial independence beckons, more than a third of the population is in poverty, unemployment remains high and wages have tumbled.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATHENS — When Dimitris Zafiriou landed a coveted full-time job two months ago, the salary was only half what he earned before Greece’s debt crisis. Yet after years of struggling, it was a step up.

headline.main: Greece’s Bailout Is Ending. The Pain Is Far From Over.
headline.print_headline: Greece’s Bailout Is Ending. The Pain Is Far From Over.

docs.abstract: The bank’s move, to ramp up the benchmark rate by 6.25 percentage points, had long been resisted by President Recep Tayyip Erdogan.
docs.snippet: The bank’s move, to ramp up the benchmark rate by 6.25 percentage points, had long been resisted by President Recep Tayyip Erdogan.
docs.lead_paragraph: Acting to stem a currency crisis that has rattled markets worldwide, Turkey’s central bank sharply raised interest rates on Thursday, defying a call by President Recep Tayyip Erdogan just hours earlier to lower borrowing costs.

headline.main: Defying Erdogan, Turkey’s Central Bank Raises Interest Rates
headline.print_headline: Turkish Bank Raises Rates, Defying Erdogan

byline.original: By Liz Alderman and Prashant S. Rao
